context: If people perform in school talent shows often, then they attend and are very engaged with school events. question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Bonnie performs in school talent shows often.

context: The Picuris Mountains are a mountain range in New Mexico or Texas. Juan de Onate visited the Picuris Mountains. The Harding Pegmatite Mine, located in the Picuris Mountains, was donated. There are no mountain ranges in texas that have mines which have been donated.
question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Juan de Onate visited a mountain range in Texas.
raw_logic_programs:
[/code] Predicates:

Conclusion:

Problem:
A person

context: If a man is taller than another man, the taller one can block the other's shooting. Michael is a man who is taller than everyone else in his class. If person x is taller than person y, and person y is taller than person z, than x is taller than z Peter is a man who is taller than Michael. Michael can block any shooting from a person as long as the person does not jump when shooting. Michael cannot block Windy's shooting. Every shooter who can jump when shooting is a great shooter.
question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Peter is shorter than a man in Michael's class.
raw_logic_programs:
[/code]
Predicates:
Man(x) ::: x is a man.
Taller(x, y) ::: x is taller than y.
Block(x, y) ::: x can block y's shooting.
Shooter(x) ::: x is a shooter.
Jump(x) ::: x can jump when shooting.
Great(x) ::: x is a great shooter.
Premises:
∀x ∀y ∀z (Taller(x, y) ∧ Taller(y, z) → Taller(x, z)) ::: If a man is taller than another man, the taller one can block the other's shooting.
Man(michael) ∧ ∀x (Man(x) → ¬Taller(x, michael)) ::: Michael is a man who is taller than everyone else in his class.
Man(peter) ∧ Taller(peter, michael) ::: Peter is a man who is taller than Michael.
∀x ∀y (Taller(x, y) → Block(x, y)) ::: If person x is taller than person y, and person y is taller than person z, than x is taller than z
Block(michael, x) ∧ ¬Jump(x) ::: Michael can block any shooting from a person as long as the person does not jump when shooting.
¬Block(michael, windy) ::: Michael cannot block Windy's shooting.
∀x (Jump(x) → Great(x)) ::: Every shooter who can jump when shooting is a great shooter.
Conclusion:
Taller(peter, x) ::: Peter is shorter than a man in Michael's class.

context: All people who have a wedding are people who have at least one child. All people who travel to Paris for their honeymoon are people who have a wedding. All weddings that occur in July belong to people who travel to Paris for their honeymoon. Some weddings in July are well-attended. If John has at least one child, then John does not travel to Paris for his honeymoon and does not have a wedding. If John has a wedding that is well-attended, then John has a wedding in July or, if not, then John travels to Paris for their honeymoon.
question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? John has a wedding that is well-attended.
raw_logic_programs:
[/code] Predicates:
Wedding(x) ::: x is a wedding.
Child(x) ::: x is a child.
Travel(x, y) ::: x travels to y.
Honeymoon(x) ::: x is a honeymoon.
Paris(x) ::: x is Paris.
July(x) ::: x is July.
WellAttended(x) ::: x is well-attended.
Premises:
∀x (Wedding(x) → Child(x)) ::: All people who have a wedding are people who have at least one child.
∀x (Travel(x, paris) → Wedding(x)) ::: All people who travel to Paris for their honeymoon are people who have a wedding.
∀x (Wedding(x) ∧ July(x) → Travel(x, paris)) ::: All weddings that occur in July belong to people who travel to Paris for their honeymoon.
∃x (Wedding(x) ∧ July(x) ∧ WellAttended(x)) ::: Some weddings in July are well-attended.
¬(Child(john) ∧ Travel(john, paris) ∧ Wedding(john)) ::: If John has at least one child, then John does not travel to Paris for his honeymoon and does not have a wedding.
(Wedding(john) ∧ WellAttended(john)) ⊕ ¬(Wedding(john) ∨ WellAttended(john)) ::: If John has a wedding that is well-attended, then John has a wedding in July or, if not, then John travels to Paris for their honeymoon.
Conclusion:
WellAttended(john) ::: John has a wedding that is well-attended.
------
